arly modern scholars who radically reassess the crises of authority, agency, and sexuality that have surrounded John Bunyan since he first began to preach and to write. In his anguished, self-conscious pursuit of salvation, Bunyan augurs the dilemmas of modernity. At the same time, he vigorously espouses dissent and liberty. The essays of this collection examine the societal and psychological fault lines in the early modern culture that Bunyan himself epitomizes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aChristian literature, EnglishxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aDissenters, ReligiouszEnglandxHistoryy17th centuryvCongresses. 4aHistory -- British. 4aLiterary Studies -- British. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAchinstein, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamden, Vera J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamden, Vera J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavies, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEzell, Margaret J. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuxon, Thomas H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorbrook, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPooley, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRudnytsky, Peter L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804768450zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768450/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles